WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Welcome to RStudio Global. Thank you so much for tuning in. I'm going to talk

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:15.200
today about the things that we can learn about ggplot2 from our data

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:21.400
visualization mishaps. So if you have spent much time visualizing data, you

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:26.520
have probably ended up with some plots that did not go to plan. Maybe you had

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:31.879
lots of overlapping blue hexagons, or text that took up the entire area of the

00:00:31.879 --> 00:00:38.080
plot, or giant hairballs. My name is Kara Woo, and I'm one of the maintainers of

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:43.560
the Accidental Art Twitter account, and I'm a contributor to ggplot2 also. So

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:49.320
I've seen a lot of plots that have gone totally wrong. The Accidental Art

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:55.439
account exists to showcase these plots, to showcase the plots gone beautifully

00:00:55.439 --> 00:01:01.959
wrong, the things that didn't work out but looked cool nonetheless. And I've

00:01:01.959 --> 00:01:07.760
seen also plots that just straight-up flopped in sometimes really subtle or

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:13.879
hard-to-diagnose ways. And so there's this whole spectrum of messed-up plots

00:01:13.879 --> 00:01:19.480
that that I've seen. And I know that these can be really frustrating, but they

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:23.680
can also be an opportunity for us to create better plots and to deepen our

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:28.360
understanding of the tools that we use to create those plots. So if you're like

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:34.360
me, then when you create a plot like the ones that I've showed, you

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:39.480
likely go to a place like Stack Overflow to find someone with a similar problem,

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:45.199
find a hopeful solution, and bring that over into your code to hopefully fix the

00:01:45.199 --> 00:01:48.760
problem that you've had. And that's great, and that's totally legitimate.

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:54.000
I'm going to argue though that when you get that working solution, it's worth

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.760
taking the time to think about how that solution fits into the conceptual model

00:01:58.760 --> 00:02:04.320
of ggplot2. My feeling is that by examining these messed-up plots that our

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:08.600
mistakes generate and how we fix them, we can deepen our understanding of

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:14.600
ggplot2's philosophy to create better visualizations faster and more reliably.

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:20.839
So what do I mean by ggplot2's philosophy? ggplot2 is a data visualization package

00:02:20.839 --> 00:02:25.160
that embodies a whole theory of visualization called the layered grammar

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:30.679
of graphics, which is based on Leland Wilkinson's grammar of graphics, but it

00:02:30.679 --> 00:02:35.479
has some specific things that are, you know, tailored to its implementation in

00:02:35.479 --> 00:02:41.679
R. Lots of visualization software gives you a bunch of different charts to choose

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:46.520
from. So you have your pie charts and your scatter plots and your line charts

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:52.080
and your bar charts, and you take the end result that you want to achieve and sort

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:59.080
of work backwards to fit your data into it. ggplot2 is not like this. ggplot2 is

00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:06.360
a more data-first approach to building visualizations, starting with, you know,

00:03:06.399 --> 00:03:14.600
principles of essentially a grammar for how to convey data in visual form. So

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:19.839
when we speak or write, we don't normally start with a sentence structure that we

00:03:19.839 --> 00:03:26.399
want to use and then fit our message into that structure. Instead, we start with

00:03:26.399 --> 00:03:31.839
some idea and we use our knowledge of grammar and syntax and vocabulary to

00:03:31.839 --> 00:03:36.880
craft the message we want to express that idea. And that is very analogous to

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:43.119
how ggplot2 works. ggplot2 lets us express our data in visual forms that might be

00:03:43.119 --> 00:03:48.559
totally novel and not fit into common, you know, bar charts and line charts and

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:55.559
common types of visualizations. This gives us a really flexible tool and a

00:03:55.559 --> 00:04:01.279
really powerful tool that we can use to create the intentional art like you see

00:04:01.279 --> 00:04:05.800
on the slide, which was built with Daniel Navarro's flametree package, which

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:11.199
itself uses ggplot2. So having this flexibility gives us a lot of power and

00:04:11.199 --> 00:04:17.799
control. And it also opens up room for, you know, mistakes and for things to not

00:04:17.799 --> 00:04:23.679
always work out the way we had in mind the first time around. There are certain

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:28.440
foibles and mistakes that come up a lot with ggplot2 that demonstrate pretty

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:33.239
common misunderstandings of how ggplot2, the package, works. And that's what I'm

00:04:33.239 --> 00:04:37.440
going to talk about today. The first one that we're going to talk about are

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:42.359
mapping mishaps. These don't have to do with geographical maps. What we're

00:04:42.359 --> 00:04:47.720
talking about here is mapping visual properties in the plot to variables in

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:54.160
our data. In the parlance of ggplot2, these mappings are called aesthetics, and

00:04:54.160 --> 00:05:00.640
they're really at the heart of ggplot2's grammar of graphics. So let's take this

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:05.600
plot. This is a plot of flipper and bill length for different species of penguins

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:10.720
in Antarctica. And in this plot, we have several different aesthetics. We have

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:15.600
position along the x-axis, which corresponds to flipper length. We have

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:20.359
position along the y-axis, which corresponds to bill length. And then we

00:05:20.559 --> 00:05:26.920
have both color and shape, which correspond to the penguin species. So one

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:30.200
thing that we might want to do with a plot like this is label these different

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:34.519
clusters. We have sort of well-isolated clusters of these data points, and maybe

00:05:34.519 --> 00:05:39.279
instead of the legend at the bottom, we want to label those clusters with which

00:05:39.279 --> 00:05:45.320
species they correspond to. And what someone will often do to achieve this is

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:51.959
add a layer to the plot where they map the text that they want to appear to the

00:05:52.399 --> 00:05:58.480
x and y positions where they want to place it. So here we have x equals 195

00:05:58.519 --> 00:06:05.119
and y equals 55. We're placing the label chinstrap. And you can see that that

00:06:05.119 --> 00:06:11.640
does work in that it places text on the plot. If we look closely, though, it

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:16.119
doesn't actually look that good. So it's pretty subtle in this example, but the

00:06:17.519 --> 00:06:22.480
quality of the text is a little bit pixelated. It doesn't look as good as the

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:28.399
points and lines that are around it. And if we were running this code live, it

00:06:28.399 --> 00:06:34.720
would actually be a little bit slow to plot. Now, like I said, it's a pretty

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:42.600
subtle change or subtle issue, but we actually get a lot of ggplot2 issues

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:49.720
opened because of this specific thing where people run into their, you know,

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:53.359
with their own plots, that the plot is really slow, that the text looks really

00:06:53.359 --> 00:06:59.239
bad. And they come to us to say, is this a bug in ggplot2? Why does it look so

00:06:59.239 --> 00:07:06.079
bad? We can illustrate what's going on here another way by using the ggrepel

00:07:06.079 --> 00:07:11.239
package, which will ensure that text on the plot does not overlap. And when we

00:07:11.239 --> 00:07:15.359
do that, we can see that we actually haven't just put a single label on the

00:07:15.359 --> 00:07:20.440
plot, we've put the whole this whole giant starburst of the same text

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:27.440
repeated hundreds of times. What's going on here is that we've actually written

00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:33.320
our label the same number of times as there are rows in our data set. In this

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:41.480
case, 344 times. By putting the text label that we want inside this AES

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:47.279
function, where AES is stands for aesthetics, we've declared a mapping

00:07:47.279 --> 00:07:53.320
between our data and the label, causing that label to repeat as many times as

00:07:53.320 --> 00:08:00.119
there are data points. So that's not great. And we can avoid this by actually

00:08:00.119 --> 00:08:04.079
using a different function called annotate, which is designed to put labels

00:08:04.079 --> 00:08:08.160
on plots just once. So it's, it's designed to do exactly what we want to do

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:13.480
just stick that label on there once not map it to the underlying data. So we tell

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:18.079
annotate that we want to place a text annotation, again, give it the position

00:08:18.119 --> 00:08:25.160
and the label. And it places that text on the plot for us. And when we zoom in, it

00:08:25.160 --> 00:08:31.559
looks much better, it would be much faster to plot as well. So that was

00:08:31.559 --> 00:08:36.799
mapping mishaps, where we misapplied these aesthetic mappings between visual

00:08:36.799 --> 00:08:43.760
elements of the plot and our data. The next common mix up is what I'll call

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:50.919
scale snafus. In ggplot2, scales convert values from the data space to the

00:08:50.919 --> 00:08:54.760
aesthetic space. So in with our aesthetics that we just talked about, we

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:58.799
declared a mapping between visual elements of the plot and values in the

00:08:58.799 --> 00:09:04.280
data, you know, shape to species, for instance, the scale controls how those

00:09:04.280 --> 00:09:10.599
data points get translated into what we see on the plot. We're going to talk

00:09:10.599 --> 00:09:15.280
about coordinate systems too, which are what draw the axes and panels in the

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:20.000
plot and generally kind of set up the 2d environment of the plot. So most plots,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:25.520
including the one that we're using for our example here, use a simple Cartesian

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:30.719
coordinate system. But other plots can use, for example, like a geographical

00:09:30.719 --> 00:09:38.719
coordinate system or polar coordinate system in the case of pie charts. So

00:09:38.719 --> 00:09:44.000
let's return to our flipper and bill length visualization. And this time, in

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.159
addition to the data points, I've added the smoothed conditional means for each

00:09:48.159 --> 00:09:52.919
species. Now let's say that we want to zoom in this plot to highlight one

00:09:52.919 --> 00:09:58.520
species and sort of focus our attention in on just one of these areas of

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:04.119
the plot. There are two ways that we can accomplish this. One is by setting limits

00:10:04.119 --> 00:10:10.679
on the scale. Here we're setting the x minimum to 200 and the x maximum we just

00:10:10.679 --> 00:10:15.719
let be whatever it normally was. And then the other way that we can zoom in this

00:10:15.719 --> 00:10:20.159
plot is by setting limits on the coordinate system. Again, setting the x

00:10:20.159 --> 00:10:27.719
minimum to 200 and letting the x max be whatever it is. When we limit the scale,

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:34.840
this is the plot that we end up with. But when we limit the coordinate system, it

00:10:34.840 --> 00:10:42.119
actually looks quite different. The data looks the same, the individual points are

00:10:42.119 --> 00:10:47.440
the same, but the statistical summary looks drastically different. And that is

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:54.799
because when we set the scale limits, any data that's outside of those limits will

00:10:54.799 --> 00:11:02.359
by default be converted to NAs. And that this scale transformation happens before

00:11:02.359 --> 00:11:07.840
any statistical summaries. So before we calculate what those smooth lines and

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:14.520
error bands look like, that data has already been converted to NAs. The

00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:19.479
coordinate system, on the other hand, when you set limits there, it really just

00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:25.840
zooms in the plot. So all the other data that was originally present is still

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:32.440
getting used, even though you can't see it on the plot. So in the first plot

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:36.559
where we set the limits on the scale, statistical summaries look different

00:11:36.559 --> 00:11:40.640
because they're based on just the few data points that are visible for the

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:45.200
species in red and purple. In the second plot though, you can imagine that all the

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:49.440
rest of the data is still there and it's still getting used and those smooth

00:11:49.440 --> 00:11:55.000
lines are extending out towards where the rest of the data is. So this is

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:00.440
clearly a case where the different ways of setting these limits have

00:12:00.440 --> 00:12:04.559
major implications for the statistical summaries that we're actually displaying

00:12:04.559 --> 00:12:12.479
on the plot. And it's important to know this. So ggplot2 does alert us to this

00:12:12.479 --> 00:12:17.359
fact and if we return to the code that generated these plots, you can actually

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:21.119
see that the former version will warn you about what's going on. It says

00:12:21.119 --> 00:12:28.760
removed 192 rows containing non-finite values. So we've gotten this warning

00:12:28.760 --> 00:12:35.880
message, but it is at times easy to gloss over these messages or ignore them and

00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:40.200
so it's useful to know how scales and coordinates handle data that's out of

00:12:40.200 --> 00:12:45.359
bounds. The last type of ggplot2 mishap that I'm going to talk about are issues

00:12:45.359 --> 00:12:52.000
with themes, theme threats. Now ggplot2's theme system is not strictly part of

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.799
the grammar of graphics because it really controls all of the non-data

00:12:56.799 --> 00:13:02.640
aspects of the plot, whereas the grammar mostly deals with how we translate

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:06.960
our data into visual form. But the theme system is really important because it is

00:13:06.960 --> 00:13:12.039
how you customize a plot to look exactly how you want it, all the way up from the

00:13:12.039 --> 00:13:18.799
text font and the background color down to small details like the length of the

00:13:18.799 --> 00:13:24.760
ticks on the axes, for example. There are dozens and dozens of things that you can

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:30.599
customize about plots in ggplot2, but it would be really cumbersome to have to

00:13:30.599 --> 00:13:36.200
specify every single one of those every single time. So ggplot2 comes with a

00:13:36.200 --> 00:13:41.719
set of default themes that are built in that you can use and a system for

00:13:41.719 --> 00:13:48.239
theme elements to inherit their values and how they look from other

00:13:48.239 --> 00:13:56.559
aspects of the theme. So let's look at an example. In our theme hierarchy of

00:13:56.559 --> 00:13:59.440
different elements that you can customize, text is one of the ones that's

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:05.159
way up at the top. In theory, this applies to all the text elements of the plot. So

00:14:05.159 --> 00:14:10.679
if we look again at our penguin plot, this plot has a number of different text

00:14:10.679 --> 00:14:18.359
elements. It has title, it has axis titles and axis text, it has legend which

00:14:18.359 --> 00:14:25.440
has some text on it as well. So all of these are within the umbrella of text. If

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:31.400
you wanted to, for example, set the font of all the text in this plot, you

00:14:31.400 --> 00:14:35.239
would want to do it up at that text level rather than having to say I want

00:14:35.239 --> 00:14:41.320
the title to be this font and the axis labels to be this font and so on. At the

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:46.919
next level of the hierarchy is, in this example, is axis text. So we went from

00:14:46.919 --> 00:14:52.880
text down to just the text that labels the axes. That's everything that is

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:58.359
outlined in blue on this slide, all the axis text elements. And in this

00:14:58.359 --> 00:15:06.599
plot, we have axes on the left, right, and bottom. At the next level of the theme

00:15:06.599 --> 00:15:13.559
hierarchy, there's axis text X and axis text Y. So this allows us to, for example,

00:15:13.559 --> 00:15:20.200
customize the Y axis while leaving the X axis alone and vice versa. And there's

00:15:20.200 --> 00:15:28.119
actually one more level, axis text X bottom, axis text X top, axis text Y left

00:15:28.119 --> 00:15:35.520
and axis text Y right. Try saying that 10 times fast. Where we can customize

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:41.919
axes for potentially on one side of the plot but not the other. So these

00:15:41.919 --> 00:15:45.719
axes can be on the bottom or the top or the left and the right or some

00:15:45.719 --> 00:15:49.679
combination thereof. And you might want to have really fine-grained control over

00:15:49.679 --> 00:15:54.520
exactly which customizations you're making. So this level allows us to

00:15:54.520 --> 00:15:59.840
do that. So let's return to our plot. So again, we're looking at these

00:15:59.840 --> 00:16:04.719
penguin measurements. And this time I've added a second axis on the right-hand

00:16:04.719 --> 00:16:10.080
side of the plot that just duplicates the axis on the left-hand side. So they're

00:16:10.080 --> 00:16:15.799
exactly the same. And now let's say that we wanted to customize the labels

00:16:15.799 --> 00:16:21.760
on this axis, on our two Y axes, so that they're maybe rotated 90

00:16:21.760 --> 00:16:26.760
degrees and right justified. So we might write something like this to customize

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:35.080
both of these axes, where we're setting axis text Y to angle equals 90,

00:16:35.080 --> 00:16:39.799
horizontal justification equals 1. And since we want to apply this to both of

00:16:39.799 --> 00:16:46.000
our Y axes, this seems like the logical way to do it. But when we look at the

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:52.960
plot, something is not quite right. The rotation has taken effect, but the

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:59.799
justification has not. So only on the left-hand side are our axis labels

00:16:59.799 --> 00:17:06.760
justified. On the right-hand side, they don't match. So why would one

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:11.959
of these changes take effect, but not the other one? And the reason for this has to

00:17:11.959 --> 00:17:16.160
do with the base theme that I'm using. So I built the theme for these plots on

00:17:16.160 --> 00:17:22.079
the default ggplot theme, theme gray. And if we printed out the whole theme, it

00:17:22.079 --> 00:17:26.319
would be like super long, so we're not going to look at all of it. But I've

00:17:26.319 --> 00:17:32.280
just put on the slide the parts of it that have to do with axis text. You

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:38.119
can see that theme gray sets the margins and the justification of axis text Y. And

00:17:38.439 --> 00:17:46.000
then it actually adjusts those details for axis text Y right. And in

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.920
particular, theme gray is setting the justification of text in axis text Y

00:17:50.920 --> 00:18:00.439
right to 0, corresponding to a left-justified text. This brings us to the

00:18:00.439 --> 00:18:04.280
crucial piece of the theme system, which is that when you're customizing theme

00:18:04.359 --> 00:18:10.239
elements, the most specific element wins. If the theme that you're using sets a

00:18:10.239 --> 00:18:15.839
specific element, like the justification of axis text Y right, then if you want to

00:18:15.839 --> 00:18:19.760
change it, you need to edit that very specific element and not any of the ones

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:25.160
above it. So in our case, theme gray sets the justification, but not the angle of

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:32.280
axis text Y right. So when we change axis text Y, the justification that we

00:18:32.319 --> 00:18:37.760
provided gets overridden by the theme that we're using. This is something that

00:18:37.760 --> 00:18:42.119
has thrown off so many people. It's thrown off me, it's thrown off other

00:18:42.119 --> 00:18:46.880
contributors to ggplot, it comes up all of the time, because it is a subtle and

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:52.239
slightly confusing aspect of how this theme inheritance works. But when you

00:18:52.239 --> 00:18:57.160
think about the fact that it's working by specificity, and not by the order in

00:18:57.160 --> 00:19:04.680
which you provide, you know, customizations to the theme, it does make

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:10.760
sense. So to get a working plot, we would need to edit axis text Y right like

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:15.680
this. So instead of setting our customizations to the axis text Y

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:21.839
element, where they'll be overridden by the theme that we're using, we customize

00:19:21.839 --> 00:19:26.880
axis text Y left and axis text Y right. And that makes sure that our

00:19:27.119 --> 00:19:33.280
customizations get applied the way we want them to. And now everything looks

00:19:33.319 --> 00:19:38.680
good on the plot. These these two axes are looking exactly the same on the left

00:19:38.680 --> 00:19:45.719
and the right. So let's recap the ggplot2 mishaps we've talked about. We have

00:19:45.719 --> 00:19:50.640
mapping mishaps where we accidentally map the data to a single visual element

00:19:50.640 --> 00:19:56.439
over and over and over again. We have scale snafus, which is where we have two

00:19:56.439 --> 00:20:00.239
different ways of setting the boundaries of a plot where one of them discards

00:20:00.239 --> 00:20:04.920
data, one of them does not. And this can affect the statistical summaries that

00:20:04.920 --> 00:20:10.000
are shown on the plot. And we have theme threats where we try to customize the

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:15.760
plot at a higher level of the theme hierarchy that then gets overridden by a

00:20:15.760 --> 00:20:19.800
more specific theme customization. We haven't gotten into all of the

00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:24.959
components of the grammar, we haven't talked about stats, geomes, position

00:20:24.959 --> 00:20:29.079
adjustments in that much detail. But if you really want to get deep into the

00:20:29.079 --> 00:20:34.040
understanding of how ggplot2 works, and all of the parts of the grammar that we

00:20:34.040 --> 00:20:38.680
haven't covered, you should definitely check out the ggplot2 book. There's a

00:20:38.680 --> 00:20:42.680
chapter in there specifically about mastering the grammar, and it will really

00:20:42.680 --> 00:20:46.920
help you build the solid foundation for understanding all of these different

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:52.719
components of ggplot2. So I want to leave you with one last piece of

00:20:52.719 --> 00:20:57.280
accidental art. It's one of my favorite patterns that comes up over and over

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:02.280
again on the accidental art Twitter page, this sort of weird geometric pattern

00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:08.000
that you often see in maps. So here we're taking data on states, trying to plot it

